Direct `===` comparisons can fail with floating-point math because many decimal values cannot be represented exactly in binary.

Use an epsilon/tolerance check instead:

```js
const a = 0.1 + 0.2;
const b = 0.3;

if (Math.abs(a - b) < Number.EPSILON) {
  console.log('equal');
}
```

For more robust code, use a configurable tolerance:

```js
function nearlyEqual(a, b, tolerance = 1e-10) {
  return Math.abs(a - b) <= tolerance;
}

if (nearlyEqual(0.1 + 0.2, 0.3)) {
  console.log('equal');
}
```

If the numbers may vary in scale, a relative comparison is better:

```js
function nearlyEqual(a, b, tolerance = 1e-10) {
  return Math.abs(a - b) <= tolerance * Math.max(1, Math.abs(a), Math.abs(b));
}
```

`Number.EPSILON` is fine for small values near 1, but a custom tolerance is usually safer.

