A binary search tree (BST) is a binary tree where, for every node:
- all values in the left subtree are **less than** the node’s value
- all values in the right subtree are **greater than** the node’s value
- both subtrees must also satisfy the same rule

This property makes searching, inserting, and deleting efficient on average because each comparison lets you discard half of the remaining subtree.

```js
function insertIntoBST(root, val) {
  if (root === null) {
    return { val, left: null, right: null };
  }

  if (val < root.val) {
    root.left = insertIntoBST(root.left, val);
  } else {
    root.right = insertIntoBST(root.right, val);
  }

  return root;
}
```

Example node shape:

```js
const root = {
  val: 4,
  left: { val: 2, left: null, right: null },
  right: { val: 7, left: null, right: null }
};

insertIntoBST(root, 5);
```

After insertion, `5` becomes the left child of `7`.

564.answer:
A heap supports a priority queue by keeping the highest- or lowest-priority element at the root, so insert and remove-min/remove-max stay efficient.

For a **min-heap**:
- It is a **complete binary tree**, usually stored in an array.
- Each parent is **<= its children**.
- The minimum element is always at index `0`.
- `insert` adds to the end, then **bubbles up**.
- `extractMin` removes the root, moves the last element to the root, then **bubbles down**.
- Both operations are **O(log n)**.

JavaScript implementation:

```js
class MinHeap {
  constructor() {
    this.heap = [];
  }

  insert(value) {
    this.heap.push(value);
    this.bubbleUp(this.heap.length - 1);
  }

  extractMin() {
    if (this.heap.length === 0) return null;
    if (this.heap.length === 1) return this.heap.pop();

    const min = this.heap[0];
    this.heap[0] = this.heap.pop();
    this.bubbleDown(0);
    return min;
  }

  bubbleUp(index) {
    while (index > 0) {
      const parentIndex = Math.floor((index - 1) / 2);
      if (this.heap[parentIndex] <= this.heap[index]) break;

      [this.heap[parentIndex], this.heap[index]] = [
        this.heap[index],
        this.heap[parentIndex],
      ];

      index = parentIndex;
    }
  }

  bubbleDown(index) {
    const length = this.heap.length;

    while (true) {
      let smallest = index;
      const left = 2 * index + 1;
      const right = 2 * index + 2;

      if (left < length && this.heap[left] < this.heap[smallest]) {
        smallest = left;
      }

      if (right < length && this.heap[right] < this.heap[smallest]) {
        smallest = right;
      }

      if (smallest === index) break;

      [this.heap[index], this.heap[smallest]] = [
        this.heap[smallest],
        this.heap[index],
      ];

      index = smallest;
    }
  }
}
```

Example:

```js
const h = new MinHeap();
h.insert(5);
h.insert(2);
h.insert(8);
h.insert(1);

console.log(h.extractMin()); // 1
console.log(h.extractMin()); // 2
console.log(h.extractMin()); // 5
```

