566.answer:
Quicksort works by choosing a **pivot**, then **partitioning** the array so values smaller than the pivot end up on one side and larger values on the other. After partitioning, the pivot is in its final sorted position, so you recursively quicksort the left and right subarrays.

A common partition scheme is:
1. Pick a pivot, often the last element.
2. Walk through the array.
3. Keep a boundary for the “smaller than pivot” region.
4. When you find a smaller element, swap it into that region.
5. At the end, swap the pivot into the boundary position.

That gives average **O(n log n)** time, though worst case is **O(n²)** if pivots are consistently poor.

```js
function quicksort(arr) {
  const a = [...arr];

  function partition(low, high) {
    const pivot = a[high];
    let i = low;

    for (let j = low; j < high; j++) {
      if (a[j] < pivot) {
        [a[i], a[j]] = [a[j], a[i]];
        i++;
      }
    }

    [a[i], a[high]] = [a[high], a[i]];
    return i;
  }

  function sort(low, high) {
    if (low >= high) return;
    const p = partition(low, high);
    sort(low, p - 1);
    sort(p + 1, high);
  }

  sort(0, a.length - 1);
  return a;
}

// Example
console.log(quicksort([5, 3, 8, 4, 2, 7, 1, 6]));
// [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]
```

