576.answer:
A trie is a tree for storing strings by shared prefixes.

- Each edge/step represents a character.
- Each node represents a prefix.
- Words that start the same share the same path.

Example: storing `cat`, `car`, and `dog` shares the `c -> a` path for the first two.

It solves problems where prefix lookup matters:
- Fast word lookup
- Prefix checks like "does anything start with `app`?"
- Autocomplete/prefix search
- Dictionary-style storage with shared prefixes

Compared with a hash set:
- `search(word)` is efficient in both
- `startsWith(prefix)` is what tries are especially good at
- Tries can use more memory because they store nodes per character

Typical time complexity:
- `insert(word)`: `O(n)`
- `search(word)`: `O(n)`
- `startsWith(prefix)`: `O(n)`
where `n` is the length of the input string.

Here’s a simple JavaScript implementation:

```js
class TrieNode {
  constructor() {
    this.children = new Map();
    this.isEnd = false;
  }
}

class Trie {
  constructor() {
    this.root = new TrieNode();
  }

  insert(word) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const ch of word) {
      if (!node.children.has(ch)) {
        node.children.set(ch, new TrieNode());
      }
      node = node.children.get(ch);
    }

    node.isEnd = true;
  }

  search(word) {
    const node = this._traverse(word);
    return node !== null && node.isEnd;
  }

  startsWith(prefix) {
    return this._traverse(prefix) !== null;
  }

  _traverse(str) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const ch of str) {
      if (!node.children.has(ch)) {
        return null;
      }
      node = node.children.get(ch);
    }

    return node;
  }
}

// Example usage
const trie = new Trie();
trie.insert("apple");

console.log(trie.search("apple"));    // true
console.log(trie.search("app"));      // false
console.log(trie.startsWith("app"));  // true
trie.insert("app");
console.log(trie.search("app"));      // true
```

