String tokenization means splitting text into meaningful pieces called tokens based on rules. A simple tokenizer might split on spaces, but real parsers need context: delimiters inside quotes usually should not split, escape sequences may change meaning, and some formats treat repeated quote characters as an escaped quote. CSV is a good example: commas separate fields, except when they appear inside quoted fields; inside a quoted field, `""` represents a literal `"`.

Here’s a simple JavaScript function that parses one CSV line correctly for those rules:

```js
function parseCsvLine(line) {
  const fields = [];
  let field = "";
  let inQuotes = false;

  for (let i = 0; i < line.length; i++) {
    const ch = line[i];

    if (inQuotes) {
      if (ch === '"') {
        if (line[i + 1] === '"') {
          field += '"';
          i++;
        } else {
          inQuotes = false;
        }
      } else {
        field += ch;
      }
    } else {
      if (ch === ',') {
        fields.push(field);
        field = "";
      } else if (ch === '"') {
        inQuotes = true;
      } else {
        field += ch;
      }
    }
  }

  fields.push(field);
  return fields;
}
```

Example:

```js
console.log(parseCsvLine('a,"b,c","d""e",f'));
// [ 'a', 'b,c', 'd"e', 'f' ]
```

