Debouncing waits for a burst of events to stop before running the callback once. Each new call resets the timer, so the callback only fires after a quiet period. In event-driven systems, this is useful for noisy inputs like typing, resize, or scroll events when you want to avoid repeated work until activity settles.

```js
function debounce(callback, delay = 300) {
  let timeoutId;

  return function debounced(...args) {
    const context = this;
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      callback.apply(context, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}
```

Example:

```js
const logSearch = debounce((value) => {
  console.log('Searching for:', value);
}, 300);

logSearch('c');
logSearch('cl');
logSearch('clo');
// Only the last call runs, 300 ms after calls stop.
```

