AVL trees are self-balancing binary search trees where, for every node, the height difference between the left and right subtrees is at most 1. This difference is the **balance factor**:

`balanceFactor = height(left) - height(right)`

If insertion makes a node unbalanced, AVL trees restore balance using rotations:

- **LL case**: inserted into left subtree of left child → right rotation
- **RR case**: inserted into right subtree of right child → left rotation
- **LR case**: inserted into right subtree of left child → left rotation on child, then right rotation
- **RL case**: inserted into left subtree of right child → right rotation on child, then left rotation

Because the tree stays balanced, search, insert, and delete are all `O(log n)`.

## Java implementation

```java
public class AVLTreeDemo {
    static class Node {
        int key;
        int height;
        Node left, right;

        Node(int key) {
            this.key = key;
            this.height = 1;
        }
    }

    static class AVLTree {
        private Node root;

        private int height(Node node) {
            return node == null ? 0 : node.height;
        }

        private int getBalance(Node node) {
            return node == null ? 0 : height(node.left) - height(node.right);
        }

        private void updateHeight(Node node) {
            node.height = 1 + Math.max(height(node.left), height(node.right));
        }

        private Node rightRotate(Node y) {
            Node x = y.left;
            Node t2 = x.right;

            x.right = y;
            y.left = t2;

            updateHeight(y);
            updateHeight(x);

            return x;
        }

        private Node leftRotate(Node x) {
            Node y = x.right;
            Node t2 = y.left;

            y.left = x;
            x.right = t2;

            updateHeight(x);
            updateHeight(y);

            return y;
        }

        public void insert(int key) {
            root = insert(root, key);
        }

        private Node insert(Node node, int key) {
            if (node == null) {
                return new Node(key);
            }

            if (key < node.key) {
                node.left = insert(node.left, key);
            } else if (key > node.key) {
                node.right = insert(node.right, key);
            } else {
                return node; // ignore duplicates
            }

            updateHeight(node);
            int balance = getBalance(node);

            // LL
            if (balance > 1 && key < node.left.key) {
                return rightRotate(node);
            }

            // RR
            if (balance < -1 && key > node.right.key) {
                return leftRotate(node);
            }

            // LR
            if (balance > 1 && key > node.left.key) {
                node.left = leftRotate(node.left);
                return rightRotate(node);
            }

            // RL
            if (balance < -1 && key < node.right.key) {
                node.right = rightRotate(node.right);
                return leftRotate(node);
            }

            return node;
        }

        public void printInOrder() {
            inOrder(root);
            System.out.println();
        }

        private void inOrder(Node node) {
            if (node == null) {
                return;
            }
            inOrder(node.left);
            System.out.print(node.key + " ");
            inOrder(node.right);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        AVLTree tree = new AVLTree();
        int[] values = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 25};

        for (int value : values) {
            tree.insert(value);
        }

        System.out.print("In-order traversal: ");
        tree.printInOrder();
    }
}
```

## Output

```text
In-order traversal: 10 20 25 30 40 50
```

That in-order output is sorted because AVL trees are still binary search trees. If you want, I can also show the tree shape after each insert or add deletion support.

