A semaphore limits how many threads can access a shared resource at the same time. It maintains a fixed number of permits; each thread must acquire one before entering the critical section and release it when done. If no permits remain, additional threads block until one is released.

In Java, `java.util.concurrent.Semaphore` does this directly. For a resource pool with 3 concurrent permits:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import java.util.concurrent.Semaphore;
import java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;

public class ResourcePoolExample {
    private final Semaphore semaphore = new Semaphore(3);

    public void useResource(String workerName) {
        try {
            semaphore.acquire();
            System.out.println(workerName + " acquired a permit. Available: " + semaphore.availablePermits());

            // Simulate resource usage
            Thread.sleep(2000);

            System.out.println(workerName + " releasing permit.");
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
            System.err.println(workerName + " was interrupted.");
        } finally {
            semaphore.release();
            System.out.println(workerName + " released a permit. Available: " + semaphore.availablePermits());
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ResourcePoolExample pool = new ResourcePoolExample();
        ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(6);

        for (int i = 1; i <= 6; i++) {
            String workerName = "Worker-" + i;
            executor.submit(() -> pool.useResource(workerName));
        }

        executor.shutdown();
        try {
            executor.awaitTermination(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        }
    }
}
```

Key point: although 6 tasks are submitted, only 3 can use the resource at once because the semaphore starts with 3 permits.

Small correctness note: in production code, only release if `acquire()` succeeded. A safer version is:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.Semaphore;

public class ResourcePool {
    private final Semaphore semaphore = new Semaphore(3);

    public void useResource() throws InterruptedException {
        semaphore.acquire();
        try {
            // access pooled resource here
        } finally {
            semaphore.release();
        }
    }
}
```

