The Strategy pattern defines a family of algorithms, encapsulates each one behind the same interface, and makes them interchangeable at runtime. It’s useful when you want to swap behavior without filling your code with `if/else` chains.

### When to use it
- Multiple ways to perform the same task
- Runtime selection of behavior
- Cleaner code than conditional branching
- Easier extension without changing existing logic

### JavaScript example: payment strategies
```js
class CreditCardPayment {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Credit Card.`);
  }
}

class PayPalPayment {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using PayPal.`);
  }
}

class BankTransferPayment {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Bank Transfer.`);
  }
}

class PaymentContext {
  constructor(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  setStrategy(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  processPayment(amount) {
    if (!this.strategy || typeof this.strategy.pay !== 'function') {
      throw new Error('A valid payment strategy is required.');
    }

    this.strategy.pay(amount);
  }
}

// Usage
const payment = new PaymentContext(new CreditCardPayment());
payment.processPayment(100);

payment.setStrategy(new PayPalPayment());
payment.processPayment(50);

payment.setStrategy(new BankTransferPayment());
payment.processPayment(200);
```

### Why this is Strategy
- `CreditCardPayment`, `PayPalPayment`, and `BankTransferPayment` are the strategies.
- `PaymentContext` is the context that uses one strategy at a time.
- The client can switch strategies without changing the context logic.

### Functional version
If you prefer plain objects/functions:

```js
const creditCardPayment = {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Credit Card.`);
  }
};

const payPalPayment = {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using PayPal.`);
  }
};

const bankTransferPayment = {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} using Bank Transfer.`);
  }
};

class PaymentContext {
  constructor(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  setStrategy(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  processPayment(amount) {
    this.strategy.pay(amount);
  }
}
```

