The singleton pattern ensures a class has exactly one instance and provides a global access point to it. It’s useful for shared resources like configuration, caches, or logging, but it should be used sparingly because it introduces global state and can make testing harder.

A thread-safe singleton in C# is best implemented with `Lazy<T>` because initialization is guaranteed to be safe and happen only once across threads.

```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;

public sealed class Logger
{
    private static readonly Lazy<Logger> _instance =
        new Lazy<Logger>(() => new Logger());

    private readonly string _logFilePath;
    private readonly object _writeLock = new object();

    private Logger()
    {
        _logFilePath = "app.log";
    }

    public static Logger Instance => _instance.Value;

    public void Log(string message)
    {
        var entry = $"[{DateTime.Now:yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss}] {message}{Environment.NewLine}";

        lock (_writeLock)
        {
            File.AppendAllText(_logFilePath, entry);
        }
    }
}

public class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        Logger.Instance.Log("Application started.");
        Logger.Instance.Log("Another log entry.");
    }
}
```

Key points:
- `sealed` prevents subclassing.
- Private constructor prevents external instantiation.
- `Lazy<Logger>` makes instance creation thread-safe.
- `lock` protects concurrent file writes.

If you want, I can also show a version using double-checked locking or one that logs asynchronously.

