The adapter pattern wraps an incompatible API and exposes the interface your code expects. It’s useful when you need to integrate legacy code without changing either the caller or the old service.

### How it works
- **Target interface**: the JSON-based contract your app wants.
- **Adaptee**: the existing legacy XML service.
- **Adapter**: translates between them.

This keeps the rest of the app talking JSON while the adapter handles XML conversion behind the scenes.

### TypeScript example
```ts
// Target interface: what the modern app expects
interface UserService {
  getUser(id: string): Promise<{ id: string; name: string; email: string }>;
}

// Legacy XML service: incompatible interface
class LegacyXmlUserService {
  async fetchUserXml(userId: string): Promise<string> {
    // Simulated legacy response
    return `
      <user>
        <id>${userId}</id>
        <name>Jane Doe</name>
        <email>jane@example.com</email>
      </user>
    `.trim();
  }
}

// Adapter: converts XML service output into the JSON shape expected by UserService
class XmlToJsonUserServiceAdapter implements UserService {
  constructor(private readonly legacyService: LegacyXmlUserService) {}

  async getUser(id: string): Promise<{ id: string; name: string; email: string }> {
    const xml = await this.legacyService.fetchUserXml(id);
    return this.parseUserXml(xml);
  }

  private parseUserXml(xml: string): { id: string; name: string; email: string } {
    const getTagValue = (tag: string): string => {
      const match = xml.match(new RegExp(`<${tag}>(.*?)</${tag}>`, "s"));
      if (!match) throw new Error(`Missing <${tag}> in XML response`);
      return match[1].trim();
    };

    return {
      id: getTagValue("id"),
      name: getTagValue("name"),
      email: getTagValue("email"),
    };
  }
}

// Client code: depends only on the JSON-based interface
async function main() {
  const legacyService = new LegacyXmlUserService();
  const userService: UserService = new XmlToJsonUserServiceAdapter(legacyService);

  const user = await userService.getUser("123");
  console.log(user);
  // { id: '123', name: 'Jane Doe', email: 'jane@example.com' }
}

main();
```

### Why this is useful
- isolates legacy integration code
- avoids rewriting old systems
- lets new code depend on clean interfaces
- makes testing easier by mocking `UserService`

If you want, I can also show the same example with a more realistic XML parser like `fast-xml-parser`.

