The command pattern turns requests into objects so you can parameterize actions, queue them, log them, and support undo without coupling the caller to the receiver.

- **Command**: an object with a common interface like `execute()` and `undo()`.
- **Receiver**: the thing that does the real work, like a `Light`.
- **Concrete commands**: wrappers around receiver actions, like `LightOnCommand` and `LightOffCommand`.
- **Invoker**: triggers commands without knowing implementation details, like a remote control.

This is useful when you want clean separation between **asking for an action** and **performing it**.

```js
class Light {
  constructor(location) {
    this.location = location;
    this.isOn = false;
  }

  on() {
    this.isOn = true;
    console.log(`${this.location} light is ON`);
  }

  off() {
    this.isOn = false;
    console.log(`${this.location} light is OFF`);
  }
}

class LightOnCommand {
  constructor(light) {
    this.light = light;
  }

  execute() {
    this.light.on();
  }

  undo() {
    this.light.off();
  }
}

class LightOffCommand {
  constructor(light) {
    this.light = light;
  }

  execute() {
    this.light.off();
  }

  undo() {
    this.light.on();
  }
}

class RemoteControl {
  constructor() {
    this.lastCommand = null;
  }

  submit(command) {
    command.execute();
    this.lastCommand = command;
  }

  undoButton() {
    if (!this.lastCommand) {
      console.log('Nothing to undo');
      return;
    }

    this.lastCommand.undo();
    this.lastCommand = null;
  }
}

// Usage
const livingRoomLight = new Light('Living room');

const lightOn = new LightOnCommand(livingRoomLight);
const lightOff = new LightOffCommand(livingRoomLight);

const remote = new RemoteControl();

remote.submit(lightOn);   // Living room light is ON
remote.submit(lightOff);  // Living room light is OFF
remote.undoButton();      // Living room light is ON
remote.undoButton();      // Nothing to undo
```

If you want, I can also show a version with a **command history stack** for multiple undos.

