Token bucket rate limiting lets traffic burst up to a fixed capacity while enforcing a long-term average rate. Each client has a bucket holding tokens; tokens are added over time at a refill rate, up to the bucket capacity. Each request consumes one token (or more, if weighted). If enough tokens are available, the request is allowed and tokens are deducted; otherwise it is rejected. This works well because it permits short bursts when the bucket has filled, but sustained traffic cannot exceed the refill rate over time.

Here’s a simple Go implementation that allows or rejects requests based on refill rate and bucket capacity:

```go
package ratelimit

import (
	"sync"
	"time"
)

type TokenBucket struct {
	mu         sync.Mutex
	capacity   float64
	tokens     float64
	refillRate float64 // tokens per second
	lastRefill time.Time
}

func NewTokenBucket(capacity int, refillRate float64) *TokenBucket {
	now := time.Now()
	return &TokenBucket{
		capacity:   float64(capacity),
		tokens:     float64(capacity),
		refillRate: refillRate,
		lastRefill: now,
	}
}

func (tb *TokenBucket) Allow() bool {
	tb.mu.Lock()
	defer tb.mu.Unlock()

	now := time.Now()
	elapsed := now.Sub(tb.lastRefill).Seconds()

	tb.tokens += elapsed * tb.refillRate
	if tb.tokens > tb.capacity {
