Use an epsilon/tolerance comparison, not direct `===` on floats.

```js
function nearlyEqual(a, b, { absTol = 1e-9, relTol = 1e-12 } = {}) {
  const diff = Math.abs(a - b);
  if (diff <= absTol) return true;
  return diff <= Math.max(Math.abs(a), Math.abs(b)) * relTol;
}

// rule: sum(items) == target
function sumEquals(items, target, tolerancePolicy) {
  const sum = items.reduce((acc, n) => acc + n, 0);
  return nearlyEqual(sum, target, tolerancePolicy);
}

console.log(0.1 + 0.2 === 0.3); // false
console.log(sumEquals([0.1, 0.2], 0.3)); // true
```

Recommended policy for a rules engine:
- Define tolerance explicitly per numeric rule.
- Support:
  - `absTol` for fixed-scale values like currency after normalization
  - `relTol` for larger magnitudes
- Prefer decimal/integer math for money if possible:
  - store cents instead of dollars
  - or use a decimal library

