Use a per-type metadata cache so reflection runs once per CLR type instead of once per object instance.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Concurrent;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Reflection;

public static class PropertyMetadataCache
{
    private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<Type, PropertyInfo[]> Cache = new();

    public static PropertyInfo[] GetSerializableProperties(Type type) =>
        Cache.GetOrAdd(type, t =>
            t.GetProperties(BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Public)
             .Where(p => p.CanRead)
             .ToArray());
}

public static class Serializer
{
    public static Dictionary<string, object?> Serialize(object obj)
    {
        var type = obj.GetType();
        var properties = PropertyMetadataCache.GetSerializableProperties(type);

        var result = new Dictionary<string, object?>(properties.Length);
        foreach (var property in properties)
        {
            result[property.Name] = property.GetValue(obj);
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

If you want to reduce overhead further, cache compiled getters too:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Concurrent;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Linq.Expressions;
using System.Reflection;

public sealed record CachedProperty(string Name, Func<object, object?> GetValue);

public static class PropertyAccessorCache
{
    private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<Type, CachedProperty[]> Cache = new();

    public static CachedProperty[] GetAccessors(Type type) =>
        Cache.GetOrAdd(type, BuildAccessors);

    private static CachedProperty[] BuildAccessors(Type type)
    {
        return type
            .GetProperties(BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Public)
            .Where(p => p.CanRead)
            .Select(p => new CachedProperty(p.Name, BuildGetter(type, p)))
            .ToArray();
    }

    private static Func<object, object?> BuildGetter(Type declaringType, PropertyInfo property)
    {
        var obj = Expression.Parameter(typeof(object), "obj");
        var cast = Expression.Convert(obj, declaringType);
        var access = Expression.Property(cast, property);
        var box = Expression.Convert(access, typeof(object));
        return Expression.Lambda<Func<object, object?>>(box, obj).Compile();
    }
}

public static class FasterSerializer
{
    public static Dictionary<string, object?> Serialize(object obj)
    {
        var accessors = PropertyAccessorCache.GetAccessors(obj.GetType());
        var result = new Dictionary<string, object?>(accessors.Length);

        foreach (var accessor in accessors)
        {
            result[accessor.Name] = accessor.GetValue(obj);
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

### Bottleneck
The slow part is calling reflection-based discovery like `type.GetProperties()` inside the hot loop for every object. Reflection metadata lookup allocates, inspects runtime type metadata, and often repeats identical work for all instances of the same type.

### Big-O
Let:
- `n` = number of objects serialized
- `p` = number of serializable properties per type

#### Before
If each serialization does property discovery again:
- Metadata discovery: `O(p)` per object
- Value extraction: `O(p)` per object
- Total: **O(n * p)**, with a large constant from repeated reflection

More explicitly:
- Repeated discovery cost: `n * O(p)`
- Repeated read cost: `n * O(p)`
- Total: **O(n * p)**

#### After
With caching:
- One-time metadata discovery per type: `O(p)`
- Per object value extraction only: `O(p)`
- Total for one type across `n` objects: **O(p + n * p)**
- Amortized per object: **O(p)**, but without repeated metadata lookup

So the asymptotic complexity is similar for a single type, but the optimization removes the repeated reflection pass and greatly reduces constant cost. If there are `t` distinct types, total becomes:
- **Before:** `O(n * p)` discovery + read work for all objects
- **After:** `O(t * p + n * p)`

### Why this helps
When `n >> t`, which is common in serializers, the cache changes metadata discovery from “once per object” to “once per type”. That usually produces a noticeable speedup and fewer allocations in tight loops.

If you want, I can also show a version using `ConditionalWeakTable<Type, ...>` or benchmark this with BenchmarkDotNet.

