The bottleneck is bubble sort: sorting 200k integers with **O(n²)** work is far too slow for a production request path. Replace it with `std::sort`, which uses an introspective sort with **O(n log n)** average and worst-case behavior suitable for large inputs.

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <vector>

void handleRequest(std::vector<int>& values) {
    std::sort(values.begin(), values.end());
    // serve request using sorted values
}
```

If the original code looked like this:

```cpp
for (size_t i = 0; i < values.size(); ++i) {
    for (size_t j = 0; j + 1 < values.size() - i; ++j) {
        if (values[j] > values[j + 1]) {
            std::swap(values[j], values[j + 1]);
        }
    }
}
```

replace that whole block with:

```cpp
std::sort(values.begin(), values.end());
```

Big-O:
- **Before:** bubble sort = **O(n²)** time, **O(1)** extra space
- **After:** `std::sort` = **O(n log n)** time, **O(log n)** stack space

For **n = 200,000**:
- Bubble sort does on the order of **40 billion comparisons**
- `std::sort` does on the order of **200,000 × log₂(200,000) ≈ 3.5 million comparison units**

So the production bottleneck is the quadratic sorting algorithm in the request-serving path; switching to `std::sort` reduces the sort cost by orders of magnitude.

