970.answer:
The bottleneck is sorting all 10M scores when you only need the largest 100.

### Before
If the code does something like:
```java
scores.sort(Collections.reverseOrder());
return scores.subList(0, 100);
```
then the cost is:
- **Time:** `O(n log n)`
- **Space:** typically `O(log n)` to `O(n)` depending on sort/input representation

For `n = 10,000,000`, that is much more work than necessary.

### Better approach
Use a **min-heap of size K** (`PriorityQueue<Integer>`) and keep only the best 100 seen so far.

### Optimized Java code
```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.PriorityQueue;

public class TopK {
    public static List<Integer> topK(List<Integer> scores, int k) {
        if (k <= 0 || scores.isEmpty()) {
            return Collections.emptyList();
        }

        PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(k);

        for (int score : scores) {
            if (minHeap.size() < k) {
                minHeap.offer(score);
            } else if (score > minHeap.peek()) {
                minHeap.poll();
                minHeap.offer(score);
            }
        }

        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>(minHeap);
        result.sort(Collections.reverseOrder());
        return result;
    }
}
```

### Why this is better
- The heap never grows beyond `k = 100`
- Each new score costs at most `O(log k)`
- Since `k` is tiny relative to `n`, this is far cheaper than sorting everything

### After
- **Time:** `O(n log k + k log k)`
  - scanning all scores: `O(n log k)`
  - final sort of the top K results: `O(k log k)`
- Since `k = 100`, this is effectively close to **`O(n)`** in practice
- **Space:** `O(k)`

### Comparison
- **Old:** `O(n log n)`
- **New:** `O(n log k)`

For 10M items and top 100:
- `log n` is much larger than `log 100`
- You avoid reordering millions of elements that will never be returned

### If input is primitive scores
If performance is critical, prefer `int[]` over `List<Integer>` to avoid boxing overhead:
```java
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.PriorityQueue;

public class TopKArray {
    public static int[] topK(int[] scores, int k) {
        if (k <= 0 || scores.length == 0) {
            return new int[0];
        }

        PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(k);

        for (int score : scores) {
            if (minHeap.size() < k) {
                minHeap.offer(score);
            } else if (score > minHeap.peek()) {
                minHeap.poll();
                minHeap.offer(score);
            }
        }

        int[] result = new int[minHeap.size()];
        for (int i = result.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            result[i] = minHeap.poll();
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

